ors come from many disciplines, including psychology, medicine, social work, physical therapy, and nursing. Their primary objective is to improve the quality of pain management for seniors, but they also urge readers to examine their own attitudes and beliefs about elderly patients, to avoid the pitfalls of ageism and to refrain from using age to rationalize inaction.The volume is loosely divided into three overlapping sections. The first addresses social, psychological and epidemiological issues. The second section deals with family issues, including their role in pain management. The final section addresses psychological and medical interventions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChronic pain. 0aPain in old age. 7aMEDICAL / Geriatrics.2bisacsh1 aAung, Steven K. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakal, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrook, Joan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrell, Betit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarkins, S. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLagua, Belinda T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeiring, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelding, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrice, D. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRivera, Lynne M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Margaret M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Ranjan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator